, Cisco, and Ramp**\n\n## **The Windsurf Acquisition Story**\n\n### **What Happened**\nThe \"Windsurf Battle\" of Summer 2025 was one of the most dramatic events in AI coding tools:\n1. **Original plan**: Windsurf was set to be acquired by OpenAI\n2. **Microsoft blocked** the deal due to product conflict concerns\n3. **Anthropic cut off** model support\n4. **Google stepped in** with a $2.4 billion valuation to acquire the core team (technology licensing only)\n5. **Cognition acted swiftly** within 48 hours to acquire Windsurf's remaining assets\n\n### **Acquisition Impact**\n- Cognition acquired **200 employees** and Windsurf's complete product line\n- Gained **$82 million in annual revenue** from enterprise clients\n- Combined **Devin + Windsurf** to create a full-stack platform with both frontend IDE and backend execution capabilities\n- Transformed from a single-agent solution to a comprehensive platform\n\n## **Founders Background**\nThe three Chinese founders (all under 30) hold impressive credentials:\n- **Scott Wu**: 3x International Olympiad in Informatics (IOI) gold medals\n- **Steve Hao**: 1x IOI gold medal\n- **Walden Yan**: 1x IOI gold medal\n- **Total**: 5 IOI gold medals among them\n\n## **Windsurf Technical Updates**\nA GitHub repository shows **Windsurf v1.3** released in **February 2026**, with installation guides for Android Termux and ARM64 Linux, featuring automatic update detection.\n\n## **Note on Aider and Continue**\nThe search results didn't return specific updates for **Aider** or **Continue** in February 2026. The results primarily focused on the Windsurf-Devin merger and Cognition.AI's growth story.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."
